---

# Overview

Digital account opening is one of the most critical customer journeys in modern banking. Failures occurring across infrastructure, workflow controls, and core banking systems lead to customer abandonment, operational inefficiencies, regulatory concerns, and increased servicing costs.

This project develops a **hypothesis-driven analytics framework** using a **MECE (Mutually Exclusive, Collectively Exhaustive)** decomposition of the account opening process to identify, quantify, and predict operational failures across multiple system layers.

Rather than treating account opening failures as a single prediction problem, each operational layer is modeled independently to identify root causes and support targeted operational interventions.

The project concludes with a **production-oriented Early Warning System** capable of detecting high-risk transactions before failures occur.

---

# Business Problem

A mobile account opening request passes through multiple operational layers before successful completion.

```
Customer
      │
      ▼
Access Layer
(Authentication, API, Network)
      │
      ▼
Maker–Checker Workflow
(Business Controls)
      │
      ▼
CBS Posting
(Core Banking System)
      │
      ▼
Account Successfully Opened
```

Failures may occur at any layer.

Traditional dashboards only report failures after they occur.

This project focuses on **predicting failures before they happen**, allowing operations teams to intervene proactively.

---

# Project Objectives

- Diagnose operational failures across multiple banking system layers
- Build hypothesis-driven predictive models instead of black-box classifiers
- Identify statistically significant operational drivers
- Prevent feature leakage during model development
- Optimize prediction thresholds using business costs rather than accuracy
- Develop an Early Warning System for real-time operational monitoring
- Demonstrate an end-to-end analytics workflow applicable to banking, consulting, and operations analytics

---

# MECE Analytical Framework

The mobile account opening journey is decomposed into four mutually exclusive operational layers.

| Layer | Objective |
|---------|-----------|
| Access Layer | Detect infrastructure-related failures |
| Maker–Checker Layer | Identify workflow and approval breakdowns |
| CBS Layer | Detect failures during core banking synchronization |
| End-to-End Layer | Measure overall operational friction |

Each layer is modeled independently before integrating insights into an overall operational risk framework.

---

# Hypothesis Framework

The project follows a structured hypothesis-driven analytical approach.

## Hypothesis 1 — Access Layer

**Null Hypothesis (H₀)**

Infrastructure characteristics such as API latency, retry attempts, authentication failures, middleware timeouts, and server conditions do **not** significantly influence access failures.

**Alternative Hypothesis (H₁)**

Infrastructure characteristics significantly increase the probability of access failures.

---

Additional hypotheses are developed for:

- Maker–Checker breakdowns
- CBS posting failures
- End-to-End operational friction

---

# Dataset

Since real banking transaction logs cannot be publicly shared, a realistic synthetic dataset was generated to simulate operational events.

## Dataset Characteristics

| Property | Value |
|----------|---------|
| Records | ~99,000 |
| Failure Layers | 4 |
| Branches | 499 |
| Channels | Mobile, Tablet |
| Infrastructure Features | API latency, retry count, server region |
| Workflow Features | TAT, field validation, caching |
| CBS Features | Synchronization status, reconciliation |
| Operational Features | Branch, channel, friction score |

The synthetic data was engineered to preserve realistic banking operational behavior while protecting confidential information.

---

# Feature Engineering

Feature engineering was designed to simulate operational signals commonly observed in digital banking platforms.

Examples include:

### Infrastructure

- API latency
- Retry count
- Server region
- Peak hour
- Hour band

### Authentication

- OTP failure
- Session timeout
- Token mismatch

### Middleware

- Middleware timeout
- External dependency failures
- Application crashes
- Client network drops

### Workflow

- Turnaround time (TAT)
- Control risk score
- Field validation errors
- Peak submission flag

### CBS

- Synchronization status
- Reconciliation flag
- Data loss flag
- API call status

